3) Decision and rationale
I choose CD 2 because its specific attributes align strongly with nearly every element I called out as important: intimate, close‑miked vocals with clear midrange (puts the lead front‑and‑center); piano/acoustic led arrangements and tasteful string backing (matches my preference for piano‑forward, lush‑but‑restrained arrangements); restrained dynamics and careful sequencing (preserves dynamics and supports album‑oriented, song‑first listening); and a remaster that preserves delicate nuance and physical‑disc fidelity (retains analog warmth and avoids modern over‑compression). In short, CD 2 delivers the intimate vocal focus, tasteful arrangements, and faithful remastering that I value.
I reject CD 1 because its principal problems—uneven/inconsistent mastering with abrupt loudness/tonal jumps, occasional recessed lead vocals, CD‑era over‑polish, and fragmented sequencing—run directly counter to my stated preferences. Inconsistent mastering and loudness jumps destroy the polished, spacious continuity I want and can make dynamics feel unnatural; recessed vocals and over‑polish bury the subtle expressive lead presence I prioritize; and fragmented multi‑era sequencing undermines the album‑level flow and song‑first presentation I prefer. The sporadic AOR gloss and potential for bombastic arrangement moments also risk introducing the aggressive or bombastic elements I avoid.
